my parents were a part of.

00:01:51.050 --> 00:01:54.560 align:middle line:90%


00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:56.780 align:middle line:84%
When the Expo called
and asked, how would you

00:01:56.780 --> 00:02:00.260 align:middle line:84%
like to do an event, sort
of like the next generation

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:03.848 align:middle line:84%
speaks out being the theme, I
said, wow, that would be great.

00:02:03.848 --> 00:02:05.390 align:middle line:84%
And they said, how
would you guys all

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:09.289 align:middle line:84%
feel about having your
parents' names mentioned

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:10.712 align:middle line:90%
in the publicity?

00:02:10.712 --> 00:02:12.920 align:middle line:84%
Or would you feel uncomfortable
with that, like you'd

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:14.300 align:middle line:90%
like to not be in their shadow?

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:17.750 align:middle line:84%
And I said, hey,
it's not a shadow.

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:21.620 align:middle line:10%
It's the ground I walk on
as I carry forth in my life.

00:02:21.620 --> 00:02:25.100 align:middle line:10%
I feel so honored to be
associated with the work

00:02:25.100 --> 00:02:26.565 align:middle line:10%
that my mom and
my dad have done.

00:02:26.565 --> 00:02:28.940 align:middle line:10%
And these two guys pretty much
seem to feel the same way,

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:32.360 align:middle line:10%
although we'll hear more
from them directly tonight.

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:37.490 align:middle line:84%
And so it is really a joy
to be able to carry forth

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:42.113 align:middle line:84%
the great work of our times
that our generation is

00:02:42.113 --> 00:02:43.280 align:middle line:90%
privileged to be able to do.

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:45.980 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of people who
are part of the '60s

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:48.130 align:middle line:90%
talk about the '60s a lot.

00:02:48.130 --> 00:02:52.172 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things
that I've often noticed

00:02:52.172 --> 00:02:54.380 align:middle line:84%
is people talk about it with
a real sense of sadness,

00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:56.660 align:middle line:84%
like there was some real
dream alive back then,

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:58.560 align:middle line:84%
and then it kind of
didn't materialize

00:02:58.560 --> 00:02:59.960 align:middle line:90%
like people hoped it would.

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:02.690 align:middle line:84%
And what I want to
say to all of you

00:03:02.690 --> 00:03:06.230 align:middle line:84%
is that the great dream
is still very much alive.

00:03:06.230 --> 00:03:08.450 align:middle line:84%
And despite the
assassinations of the '60s,

00:03:08.450 --> 00:03:11.660 align:middle line:84%
despite the cultural
ebbs and flows,

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:14.480 align:middle line:84%
despite the consumerism,
and apathy, and the despair,

00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:18.620 align:middle line:84%
and the cynicism that
seems so rampant today,

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:21.680 align:middle line:84%
there is still so much hope
and so much possibility.

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.290 align:middle line:84%
And there are still so many
people doing incredible work.

00:03:24.290 --> 00:03:25.940 align:middle line:10%
And those of us who
are young today,

00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:29.090 align:middle line:10%
who are growing up
into this world,

00:03:29.090 --> 00:03:31.490 align:middle line:10%
have not only the
problems of our times

00:03:31.490 --> 00:03:35.330 align:middle line:10%
to reckon with but also
have the great work of all

00:03:35.330 --> 00:03:40.040 align:middle line:10%
who have gone before us to
learn from and to support us.

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:42.720 align:middle line:84%
